  "body": "There is a scenario where a Kubernetes cluster is stretched on two different locations (Datacenter) and we want to have 4 replicas, with 2 per Datacenter.\r\n\r\nThis can be achieved by the following CRUSH rule:\r\n\r\n```\r\nrule two_rep_per_dc {\r\n        id 1\r\n        type replicated\r\n        min_size 1\r\n        max_size 10\r\n        step take root\r\n        step choose firstn 0 type datacenter\r\n        step chooseleaf firstn 2 type host\r\n        step emit\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nHere is a little CRUSH playground to simulate the placement.\r\nFirst initialize a CRUSH map, representing our topology:\r\n\r\n```\r\ncrushtool -o crushmap --build --num_osds 18 host straw 3 datacenter straw 3 root straw 0\r\n```\r\n\r\nDecompile the map:\r\n\r\n```\r\ncrushtool -d crushmap -o map.txt\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen add the following rule:\r\n\r\n```\r\nrule two_rep_per_dc {\r\n        id 1\r\n        type replicated\r\n        min_size 1\r\n        max_size 10\r\n        step take root\r\n        step choose firstn 0 type datacenter\r\n        step chooseleaf firstn 2 type host\r\n        step emit\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nRun a placement test:\r\n\r\n```\r\ncrushtool -i crushmap --test --show-mappings\r\n```\r\n\r\nIt's going to test over 1024 placement by default and will give back \"CRUSH rule 1 x 1023 [11,14,3,2]\" that:\r\n\r\n- Where OSD 11 is on host 3 in DC 0\r\n- Where OSD 14 is on host 4 in DC 0\r\n- Where OSD 3 is on host 0  in DC 1\r\n- Where OSD 2 is on host 1  in DC 1\r\n\r\n\r\nRook needs to be able to add such rule.",
